            "response_id": "resp_0b3a39169587d93d006a3ebc29d42081969d5755795b8a8911",
            "role": "assistant",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "A “sales record” typically refers to a row-level transaction that documents a sale event (often at the invoice, order, or line-item level). It’s commonly used for reporting revenue, units, discounts, and customer/product performance over time.\n\nI attempted to pull the specific sales-record tables/fields from your Fabric workspace, but the query failed due to a technical issue, so I can’t describe *your* exact dataset structure yet【6:0†source】.\n\nIn general, sales records usually include:\n\n- **Identifiers:** order/invoice ID, line item ID, customer ID, product/SKU ID, store/region ID  \n- **Dates:** order date, ship date, invoice date (and sometimes time)  \n- **Quantities & money:** quantity sold, unit price, gross sales, discount, net sales, tax, shipping, total  \n- **Status & channel:** order status (paid/returned/cancelled), sales channel (online/retail/partner)  \n- **Cost & margin (if available):** unit cost, COGS, gross margin  \n\nCommon ways they’re summarized:\n- **Daily/weekly/monthly revenue**\n- **Units sold by product/category**\n- **Average order value (AOV)**\n- **Discount rate and return rate**\n- **Gross margin by product/region/channel**\n\nIf you tell me what you mean by “sales records” in your context (e.g., *orders vs invoice lines*, and any table names you know), I can run a more targeted query next and describe the exact columns and example aggregations.",
